gov.usgs.anss.filter

Class LHDerivedProcess

  • java.lang.Object
    • java.lang.Thread
      • gov.usgs.anss.filter.LHDerivedProcess
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.lang.Runnable

    public class LHDerivedProcess
extends java.lang.Thread
    This class computers a derived LH from some BH or HH channel. Each instance is a single channel. It attempts to phase sync the derived to the actual by adjusting its computation to the set of samples which will produce a 1 sps sample as close to the one set via setPhase() from the LH channel. The data are forwarded when ever 10 or so of them have been computed.

    There is a warmup phase that covers 2 times the expected delay and no data is generated during the warmup. If a phase shift in the LH to derived LH occurs, the warmup is restarted to allow it to get back in phase. So gaps in the derived LH are likely caused by this algorithm.

    Only HydraOutputer (scheduled for obsoletion) and LHDerivedToQueryMom are known to use this class. In the long run, the HydraOutputer should no longer be allowed to derived LH as this feature is not longer needed to put such channels on the edge wire.

    The input methods processToLH put the miniSEED onto a queue. This queue is emptied by the run() method and the data are actually processed in runProcessToLH(). This method also implements an out-of-order queue to allow the process to handle up to 10 packets of OOO data before putting a gap in and forcing a new warm up.
